We are going to build a **furniture e-commerce mobile application called Shopistry**. The goal of this project is to demonstrate **professional Flutter architecture and clean, maintainable code** that reflects real-world production standards.

The application will be developed using **Clean Architecture**, separating the project into three clear layers: **presentation, domain, and data**. Each layer will have a distinct responsibility, making the codebase easier to maintain, test, and expand in the future. This structure ensures the application can scale smoothly as additional features or services are introduced.

For state management, the project will use **Bloc** to handle events and state transitions in a predictable and structured manner. **Riverpod** will be used for dependency injection and for providing shared services across the application. This combination keeps components loosely coupled while maintaining a clear and organized flow of data.

To encourage safer and more expressive error handling, the project will incorporate **fpdart**. This enables the use of functional programming constructs such as `Either` to manage success and failure states, reducing reliance on traditional exception handling patterns and making the logic easier to reason about.

To ensure the application works consistently across different device sizes, **ScreenUtil** will be used to support responsive layout scaling.

The application will use a **single theme called Taupical**. This theme will consist of **different shades of taupe and grey**, and it will serve as the unified visual foundation of the app. In addition, the project will include a **robust text theme class**, implemented with the **Google Fonts package**, to maintain consistent typography across the entire application.

Although the application will not connect to a real backend service, it will include **realistic and comprehensive demo data** that reflects the structure and behavior of a real e-commerce system. This allows the app to behave like a complete product during development and demonstration.

At the same time, the project will be structured **as if a real backend already exists**. All backend-related operations—such as retrieving products, loading categories, managing the cart, handling wishlists, and processing orders—will be defined through **repositories, data sources, and use cases** within the architecture.

These backend functions will be fully written and integrated into the system, but their implementations will use **mocked or locally generated data** instead of real API calls. This approach ensures that when a backend service is eventually introduced, the integration process will simply involve replacing the mock implementations with real network requests.

The application will include key e-commerce capabilities such as product browsing, category organization, search functionality, wishlist management, cart operations, and a simulated checkout process.

Overall, Shopistry will demonstrate how to build a **structured, scalable Flutter application** that follows solid architectural principles, applies functional programming practices, and mirrors the workflow of a real-world production project while remaining ready for future backend integration.
